column168: Description Of Events

ON ARRIVAL AT THE FT. MEYERS TERMINAL THE CARTON WAS CRUSHED.  CANTAINED HAD LEAKED INTO THE CARDBOARD AND WAS DRY DUE TO EVAPORATION. AWAITING DISPOSITION FROM THE SHIPPER.  ORIGIN TERMINAL INSTRUCTED ON PROPER LOADING.
DRUM HAD THE WELD BREAK AND LEAKED A TOTAL OF 10 GALLONS.  PRODUCT CLEANED UP WITH DRY ABSORBANT.  FREIGHT WAS TAPED AND PLACED IN HAZARDOUS MATERIAL BAY.  AWAITING DISPOSITION OF FREIGHT.

EMPLOYEE MADE DELIVERY TO AN EXPORT TERMINAL.  THEIR OPERATOR MOVED THE SKID WHICH CONTAINED THE PRODUCT AND PUNCTURED 1 BAG. PRODUCT WAS TAPED AND THE 1/2 CUP WAS SWEPT AND ALL RETURNED TO TERMINAL. AWAITING DISPOSITION FROM SHIPPER.

A MR. JOHNSON, CHIEF ENGINEER AT BLDG.  500 AT WALTER REED ARMY HOSPITAL, TOLD OUR DRIVER THE LOAD WOULD FIT INTO THE TANK WHICH ONE OF MR. JOHNSON'S PEOPLE HAD STUCK THE TANK BEFORE OUR DRIVER STARTED TO UNLOAD. AFTER UNLOADING 2500 GALLONS THE TANK FILLED UP CAUSING SPILLAGE AT THE VENT PIPE.  THE SPILL WAS CAUSED BY AN IMPROPER STICK READING WHICH MR. JOHNSON ACCEPTED FULL RESPONSIBILITY. THE FIRE DEPT. AT WALTER REED HOSPITAL RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND CLEANED UP THE SPILL.  OUR DRIVER WAS INSTRUCTED TO PUT THE BALANCE OF THE LOAD IN ANOTHER TANK.
DURING UNLOADING, DOCKWORKER NOTICED A SMALL LEAK ON THE BOTTOM AROUND THE SEAM.  THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS PLACED INSIDE A RECOVERY DRUM AND HELD FOR DISPOSITTION.

column42: ETHANOL OR ETHYL ALCOHOL OR ETHANOL SOLUTIONS OR ETHYL ALCOHOL SOLUTIONS
column168: DOCKWORKER FOUND ONE WET CARTON DURING UNLOADING AND NOTIFIED SUPERVISOR. THE AREA WAS ISOLATED AND THE MATERIAL IDENTIFIED.  CHEMTREC WAS CONTACTED ALONG WITH THE SHIPPER.  ALL SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP AS INSTRUCTED.  THE CONTAMINATED MATERIALS WERE PLACED INSIDE A REPACKED DRUM WAN ARE BEING HELD PENDING DISPOSITION.

OUR DRIVER ARRIVED AT CUSTOMER FOR DELIVERY.  STOPPED AT GATE TO SIGN IN. WHEN THE DRIVER EXITED THE CAB, HE NOTICED A NOISE COMING FROM THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  DRIVER OPENED REAR CABINET DOOR AND FOUND THE #10 PIGTAIL LINE CRACKED.  PRODUCT WAS SEEPING BY THE SHUT-OFF VALVE AND VERY SLIGHTLY FROM THE CRACK.  CUSTOMER HM TEAM WASHED REAR OF CABINET UNTIL OUR MECHANIC ARRIVED ON THE SCENE.  MECHANIC CUT AND CRIMPED THE CRACKED LINE. HE THEN PLACED A BLOCK IN THE VALVE TO SECURE THE #10 TUBE.  DELIVERY WASN'T MADE AND THE TRAILER RETURNED TO NEW ORLEANS, LA, FOR ANALYSIS WITHOUT INCIDENT.  INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT ROAD VIBRATION CAUSED LINE TO THE PIGTAIL TO CRACK.  THE PIGTAIL AND VALVE SEAT ON THE #10 TUBE WAS REPLACED AND THE TRAILER RETURNED TO SERVICE.

NO FUTURE DELIVERIES WILL BE MADE WHEN OWNER IS NOT PRESENT.

THE DRUM WAS NOT VISIBLE WHEN EMPLOYEE WAS UNLOADING THE PALLETS. UPON SEEING THE DRUM WAS PUNCTURED, THE EMPLOYEE IMMEDIATELY LAID DRUM ON SIDE TO ELIMINATE ANY LARGE AMOUNT OF LEAKAGE.

DRIVER ARRIVED AT NIAGARA FALLAS WATER AND ASKED FOR DIRECTIONS WHERE TO PUMP OFF.  THE GAURD SENT HIM TO THE PROEPR AREA.  THE OPERATOR ARRIVED AND SHOWED THE DRIVER WHAT LINE TO HOOK UP TO AND SIGNED THE DOCUMENTS INDICATING THE SAME.  THE DRIVER THEN PROCEEDED TO HOOK UP AND AGAIN ASKED THE OPERATOR IF IT WAS OKAY TO START PUMPING.  THE OPERATOR GAVE PERMISSION. THE DRIVER PUMPED APPROXIMATELY 5 MINUTE WHEN THE RUPTURE DISK BLEW ON THE TANKER ALLOWING 500 GALLONS OF HFS TO SPILL.  THE OPERATOR HAD HOOKED THE DRIVER TO THE WRONG LINE WHICH WAS CLOSED ATOP A BUILDING THREE STORIES UP.  AS PRESSURE BUILT UP, IT FILLED THE LINE AND TANKER AND BLEW THE RUPTURE DISCK CAUSING THE SPILL.  THE DRIVER SHUT DOWN THE AIR SYSYTEM IMMEDIATELY.  THE SPILL WAS DYKED AND OCCIDENTAL CHEMICALS CALLED FOR RESPONSE AND EMERGENCY PHONE NUMBERS WERE CALLED.  THE HFS WAS ABSORBED WITH NEUTRALIZER.  THE RUPTURE DISK PERFORMED AS IT SHOULD HAVE PREVENTING RUPTURE OF THE TANKER.  WE RECOMMENED TO THE CUSTOMER TO FIND A CLEAR WAY TO MARK THE DELIVERY AREA TO PREVENT INCIDENTS IN THE FUTURE.

WHILE SECURING PACKAGE IN THE AIRCRAFT CONTAINER, THE NET PULLED THE PACKAGE OVER.  THE PACKAGE WAS ON THE FLOOR OF THE AIRCRAFT.  THE PACKAGE WAS 16 INCHES TALL.  THE VALVE ON THE EXTINGUISHER FAILED WHICH MADE THE INSIDE CONTAINER PROPEL ITSELF THROUGH THE FIBERBOARD BOX.  THE CYLINDER MOVED AROUND INSIDE THE CONTAINER UNTIL THE CONTENTS WERE EXPELLED.  THE CONTAINER WAS IN THE WAREHOUSE AT THE TIME.  THE PACKAGE NEVER WAS TRANSPORTED BY AIR.  ONE EMPLOYEE HAD A SLIGHT BRUISE ON THE KNEE BUT REQUIRED NO HOSPITALIZATION.  THE PACKAGE WAS HELD AND THE SHIPPER CONTACTED FOR DISPOSITION.

OUR INVESTIGATION REVEALS THAT WHEN TRAILER WAS BEING LOADED, A MEASURING STICK WAS USED TO CHECK IMAGE OF PRODUCT.  THE STICK CRACKED INNER RUBBERLINED.  WHILE THE TRAILER WAS BEING AIR UNLOADED IT DEVELOPED A LEAK BY THE BOTTOM WHERE TANK WAS MEASURED.  DRIVER COLLECTED MOST OF THE PRODUCT INTO BUCKET AND FINISHED UNLOADING.  AREA WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH LIME AND DISPOSED OF IN THEIR WATER TREATMENT PLANT.

WHEN TRAILER WAS OEPNED AT DOCK A STRONG ODOR WAS NOTICED.  THE TRAILER WAS FIRST AIRED OUT THEN UNLOADED.  WHEN THE SKID CONTAINING THE SODIUM BROMATE WAS REACHED WE SAW THE PRODUCT ON THE FLOOR.  DRUM WAS PLACED IN AN OVERPACK DRUM AND SENT TO CONSIGNEE PER BURT CHILDS OF SHIPPER.

column168: THE DRIVER OF THE TANK TENDER TRUCK LOST CONTROL OF THE VEHICLE, COMING OUT OF AN "S" CURVE AND ENTERED THE ROAD DITCH.  THE VEHICLE OVERTURNED CAUSING THE TANK TO ALSO OVERTURN AND START TO LEAK A DILUTE CHEMICAL OUT OF THE TANK VENT AND SEEP OUT OF THE FILL HATCH.  THE DRIVER CALLED FOR HELP BY RADIO.  HELP ARRIVED WITHIN 10 MINUTES AND THEY PLUGGED THE VENT PIPE, PUT PRESSURE ON THE FILL HATCH AND PUT UP AN EARTHED DIKE TO PREVENT RUN-OFF THROUGH THE ROAD DITCH. A TANK AND PUMP WAS THEN USED TO REMOVE THE REMAINDER OF THE LIQUID FROM THE OVERTURNED TANK.  THE TANK WAS THEN UP-RIGHTED AND THE REMAINDER OF THE LINE WAS PUMPED OUT. WHILE THE WORK ON CONTAINMENT STARTED, OFFICE PERSONNEL CONTACTED THE FOLLOWING AGENCIES: NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER 1-800-424-8802 CHEMTREC                 1-800-424-9300 GROWMARK MARSHALL COUNTY SHERIFF MARSHALL COUNTY E.S.D.A. BELL PLAIN ROAD COMISSIONER THE NEXT MORNING, SOIL THAT HAD ANY POSSIBLE CHEMICAL RESIDUE WAS DUG UP AND TAKEN TO AN INSIDE BIN AND THE HOLE WAS FILLED IN.  ERIC ACKERMAN, P.E. OF THE ILLINOIS ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AGENCY WAS ON SITE AT THE TIME OF THE EXCAVATION.

column168: WASTE HYDROCHLORIC ACID (SPENT PICKLE LIQUOR - HAZARDOUS WASTE CODE K062) WAS TRANSPORTED FROM THE WHEELING PITTBURGH STEEL CORPORATION'S ALLENPORT, PA PLANT TO THE MILL SERVICE INC., YUKON PLANT ON JUNE 3, 1991.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE MILL SERVICE PLANT, THE SHIPMENT WAS SAMPLED THROUGH THE TOP HATCH FOR SHIPMENT WAS SAMPLED THROUGH THE TOP HATCH FOR SHIPMENT VERIFICATION PURPOSES.  THE VEHICLE WAS THEN PARKED WITHOUT UNLOADING THE SHIPMENT; UNLOADING WAS TO BE PERFORMED LATER IN THE DAY.  WHEN THE DRIVER INVOLVED IN THE SPILL ON JUNE 6, 1991 REPORTED TO WORK, HE PROCEEDED OUT THE GATE WITH THE VEHICLE.  THE VEHICLE HAD INADVERTENTLY NOT BEEN UNLOADED IN THE INTERIM.  A RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 15 GALLONS  OF WASTE ACID OCCURRED FROM THE TOP HATCH ONTO THE ROAD SURFACE AS THE VEHICLE CLIMBED AND DESCENDED A GRADE.  THE TOP HATCH HAD APPARENTLY NOT BEEN COMPLETELY SECURED AFTER SHIPMENT SAMPLING ON JUNE 3, 1991, A FACT WHICH HAS NOT DISCOVERED DURING THE PRE-TRIP INSPECTION BY THE DRIVER ON JUNE 6, 1991. THE DRIVER NOTICED THE RELEASE IN THE VEHICLE MIRRORS AS HE PROCEEDED ALONG LR64278.  HE STOPPED THE VEHICLE AT THE BOTTOM OF THE GRADE, (INTERSECTION OF LR64278 AND LR 970) SECURED THE TOP HATCH AND RETURNED TO THE YUKON PLANT.  HE NOTIFIED MSI MANAGEMENT IMMEDIATELY AND A CLEAN-UP CREW FROM THE YUKON PLANT TOOK ACTION WITHIN MINUTES.  THE ROAD SURFACE WAS MOPPED BY HAND AND SUBSEQUENTLY CLEANED WITH A MECHANICAL WET SWEEPING UNIT WITH VACUUM ATTACHMENT.  ALL MATERIALS WERE TRANSPORTED TO THE YUKON PLANT FOR TREATMENT/DISPOSAL .  (MILL SERVICE OPERATES A HAZARDOUS WASTE TREATMENT FACILITY AND AN ASSOCIATED WASTE DISPOSAL UNIT AT THE YUKON PLANT UNDER AUTHORITY OF THE UNITED STATES ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AGENCY AND THE PENNSYLVANIA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL RESOURCES).  NO HEALTH RISKS WERE ASSOCIATED WITH THE SPILL AND NO EVACUATIONS WERE REQUIRED. SINCE THE INCIDENT, ALL DRIVERS HAVE BEEN REMINDED OF THE REQUIREMENT TO PERFORM COMPLETE PRE-TRIP INSPECTIONS AND TO COMPLETELY SECURE ALL HATCHES AND VALVES ON TANK TRUCKS AT ALL TIMES.

column168: THE UNIT WAS WET BOUND ON US 12 IN IDAHO ABOUT 1/4 MILE EAST OF MM 164 WHEN THE DRIVER ENTERED A LEFT HAND CURVE.  ABPOUT 3/4 WAY THROUGH THE CURVE THE SECOND TRAILER WENT INTO THE RIGHT HAND DITCH AND UPSET, HITTING A ROCK WHICH RIPPED THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE TRAILER OPEN.  WHEN THE UNIT CAME TO STOP PRODUCT WAS SPILLING OUT OF THE TRAILER AT THE RATE OF 10 GALLONS PER MINUTE.  THE ODAHO TRANSPORTATION DEPT. MAINTENANCE AND FOREST SERVICE SERVICE PERSONEL SHOWED UP AT THE SCENE AND BUILT DIKES TO CONTAIN THE SPILL.  AN ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR, ENVIROCON, INC. FROM MISSOULA WAS CONTACTED AND SUPERVISED THE CLEAN-UP OPERATION.  THE TRAILER WAS HAULING 2750 GALLONS OF PRODUCT.  THERE WAS ABOUT 150 TO 200 GALLONS LEFT IN THE TRAILER.  A VACUUM TRUCK RECOVERED FROM 2400 TO 2500 GALLONS OF PRODUCT.  APPROXIMATELY 50 YARDS OF SOIL WAS EXCAVATED AND THE AREA TESTED AND THEN BACKFILLED WITH FRESH SOIL.

column168: WHILE PLACING A TOTE BIN INTO TRAILER #19-367 FORKLIFT OPERATOR NOTICED LIQUID COMING FROM BOTTOM OF UNIT.  HE RAISED THE UNIT AND PLACED A DRUM UNDER THE LEAK TO CAPTURE THE SPILL.  UPON INVESTIGATION IT WAS FOUND THAT THE FORK HAD SLIPPED BETWEEN THE BOTTOM OF THE TOTE AND THE PLATE WHICH PROTECTS THE VALVE, AND CRACKED THE PIPE LEADING FROM THE TOTE INTO THE VALVE.  THE PLATE WHICH IS SUPPOSED TO PROTECT THE VALVE AREA SHOULD BE MOUNTED UP AGAINST THE BOTTOM OF THE TOTE BIN SO THE FORKS COULD NOT GET THROUGH TO DO THIS TYPE OF DAMAGE.  IT COULD ALSO BE RECOMMENDED THAT A SIGN BE PLACED ON THE SIDE OF THE TOTE OPPOSITE THE VALVE AREA "DO NOT FORK FROM THIS END".

column168: WHILE UNLOADING TOTE TANK FROM INBOUND TRAILER DOCKWORKER INSERTED FORKLIFT BLADES UNDER THE TANK, BEGAN TO LIFT AND TANK TIPPED FORWARD. THE LIFTING/TILTING ACTION CAUSED THE LID AND LOCK RING TO POP OFF THE TANK WHICH CAUSED SOME OF THE LIQUID TO SPILL OUT OF THE TANK.  IN ADDITION WHEN DOCKWOEKER OBSERVED WHAT HAD HAPPENED HE HURRIDLY ATTEMPTED TO SET THE TANK BACK DOWN ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR, HOWEVER, THIS SUDDEN ACTION DOWNWARD IN A TILTED POSITION CAUSED MORE OF THE LIQUID TO SPILL FROM THE TANK.  UPON INVESTIGATING WHAT THE CAUSE OF THE SPILL WAS IT WAS OBSERVED THAT THE LID AND LOCKRING MECHANISM ON THE RING APPEARED TO BE STRIPPED WHICH MADE THE LOCKRING LOOSE AND THEREBY CAUSING THE LID TO BE UNSECURE.

column168: 41. R. FAILURE OF A WLEDED JOINT IN THE HEAT AFFECTED ZONE -- WHILE ENROUTE TO SPARROWS POINT, MARYLAND FROM REIDSVILLE, NORTH CAROLINA, TRAILER 5204 INCURRED AN INNER TANK PRESSURE RISE AND SUBSEQUENT PRODUCT RELEASE DUE TO A FAIILURE OF THE LIQUID LEVEL GAUGE LIQUID LINE AT THE REAR HEAD WITHIN THE ANNULAR SPACED IN THE HEAT AFFECTED ZONE OF THE WELD WHERE THE LIQUID LINE PENETRATED THE OUTER REAR HEAD OF THE TRAILER.  THIS FAILURE RESULTED IN ANNULAR SPACE VACUUM LOSS AND SUBSEQUENT LOSS OF THE INSULATING CAPABILITIES OF THE VESSEL.  THE FAILURE ALLOWED COLD PRODUCT TO ENTER THE ANNULAR SPACE AND VAPORIZE WHICH RESULTED IN PRODUCT LOSS THROUGH THE OUTER VESSEL RLIEF PORT.  INNER VESSEL PRESSURE ALSO INCREASED DUE TO THE LOSS OF INSULATING CAPABILITIES RESULTING IN THE RISE OF INNER VESSEL PRESSURE REQUIRING MANAUAL VENTING OF PRODUCT TO THE ATMOSPHERE. WITH THE HELP OF THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE PEOPLE FROM FAIR FAX, VIRGINIA, THE PRODUCT WAS EMPTIED AND VAPORIZED TO THE ATMOSPHERE.  THE UNIT WAS SECURED AND ESCORTED TO AIR PRODUCTS' FACILITY IN BLADENSURG, MARYLAND.  THE UNIT WAS THEN TRANSPORTED TO BOSTON, MASSACHUSETTS, FOR WARRANTY REPAIRS BY THE MANUFACTURER.

THE BOX WAS BROUGHT OVER FROM THE SOUTH CENTER.  THE SIDE OF THE BOX WAS WET.  WE OPENED THE BOX TO FIND 4 LQT. CANS WITHOUT CLIPS.  ONE POPPED OPEN WE HAMMERED LID BACK ON AND OVER BOXED THE PACKAGE WITH PLASTIC AND NEW BOX WAS SENT BACK TO THE SHIPPER AS DAMAGED.  ISP CARD FILED.

WHILE LOADING PRODUCT FROM CUSTOMER'S STORAGE TANK TO CARGO TANK, PRODUCT OVERFLOWED DUE TO AN IMPROPER METER SETTING WHICH RESULTED IN AN APPROXIMATE 10 GALLON SPILL.  ALL PRODUCT WAS RETAINED AND PROPERLY CLEANED UP BY CUSTOMER PERSONNEL.
6/27 REPORT THANT T/C WAS VENTING CONTINUOUSLY.  I CONTACTED SHIPPER WHI IN TURN SET UP FOR TANK TRUCKS TO OFF LOAD PRODUCT ON MORNING OF 6/28. THIS RELEIVED PRESSURE AND ALLOWED LEAK TO STOP.

CLERK CONTACTED ME ABOUT VAPORS EMINATING FROM T/C.  CREW EVIDENTLY SMELLED SOMETHING WHEN THEY WET TO MOVE CARS.  I INVESTIGATED AND FOUND DOME BOLTS LOOSE.  I TIGHTENED DOWN DOME BOLTS AND SENT CARS ONTO DESTINATION.

DRIVER WAS ATTEMPTING TO OFFLOAD DRUM FROM SEMITRAILER TO FREIGHT DOCK, AS HE LEANED THE DRUM APPROXIMATELY ONE HALF OF THE CIRCUMFERENCE OF THE DRUM BOTTOM CRACKED.  CONTENTS OF THE DRUM WERE DUMPED ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR. PERSONNEL AT THE VOLVO TRUCK PLANT CONTACTED THE SHIPPER VIA THE EMEREGENCY RESPONSE TELEPHONE NUMBER LISTED ON THE BILL OF LADING AND HANDLED THE SPILL IN ACCORDANCE WITH NALCO INSTRUCTIONS.  THIS MATERIAL IS ROUTINELY HANDLED IN VOLVO'S SPRAY BOOTH OPERATIONS AND PRESENTED A VERY LIMITED PROBLEM. SPILLED MATERIAL WAS DILUTED WITH COPIOUS AMOUNTS OF WATER AND PRESENTED NO HAZARD TO THE ENVIRONMENT.

column168: DRIVER MISCALCULATED THE SIZE OF THE UST AT THE CONOCO STATION.  DURING THE UNLOADING OPERATION, HE OVERFILLED THE TANK CAUSING 22 GALLONS TO LEAK ONTO THE PAVEMENT.  THE PAVEMENT WAS BLOCKED OFF WIH DIRT TO KEEP THE FUEL FROM ESCAPING OFF THE PROPERTY.  FOAM WAS APPLIED BY THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT TO PREVENT A FIRE HAZARD.  VACUUM TRUCK WAS USED TO WASH THE PAVEMENT.  LIQUID WAS PICKED UP AND BROUGHT BACK TO TEMINAL TO BE INJECTED INTO PRODUCT SYSTEM.  DIRT WAS BROUGHT TO TERMINAL FOR AERATION.

column168: AT APPROX. 0650 HOURS, WED. JUNE 12, 1991, EMPLOYEES AT THE CONRAIL PAVONIA RAIL YD. IN CAMDEN, NJ, NOTICED AN ODOR AND LEAK OF PRODUCT FROM TANK CAR DUPX 14619 (NITRATING ACID MIXTURE).  TANK CAR WS ISOLATED AND SHIPPER NOTIFIED. RESPONSE PERSONNEL FROM THE SHIPPER (DUPONT) ARRIVED TO THE LOCATION OF THE TANK CAR AT APPROXIMATELY 1000 HOURS AND UPON EXAMINATION FOUND A DEFECTIVE LIQUID LINE GASKET WHICH ALLOWED PRODUCT TO LEAK FROM THE CAR. GASKET WAS REPLACED AND CAR WAS CLEARED FOR TRANSPORTATION AT 1100 HOURS, JUNE 12, 1991.  TANK CAR WAS RETURNED TO SHIPPERS LOCATION TO PRESSURE CHECK THE CAR. CONRAIL EMPLOYEE E. ADAMS (TRAINMAN) COMPLAINED OF A SORE THROAT AND HEADACHE AFTER ALLEDGELY INHALING PRODUCE FUMES.  EMPLOYEE WAS TREATED AND RELEASED BY DR. SIDLUCK AT KENNEDY MEMORIAL HOSPITAL IN WASHINGTON TOWNSHIP, NJ.  THIS INCIDENT HAS BEEN REPORTED TO THE FEDERAL RAILROAD ADMINISTRATION AS A LOST TIME INJURY INVOLVING LOST WORK DAYS.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 1850 HOURS, MONDAY, JUNE 24, 1991, THE CREW OF CONRAIL TRAIN SLSE-4 OBSERVED TANK CAR UTLX 80020 (ARGON, REFIGERATED LIQUID) VENTING PRODUCT.  TANK CAR WAS SITUATED TEN CARS FROM THE REAR END OF TRAIN.  TRAIN STOPPED AT SHERMAN DR. IN INDIANAPOLIS AND CHEMTREC, SHIPPER AND INDIANAPOLIS FIRE DEPT. NOTIFIED. UPON ARRIVAL & ASSESSING THE SITUATION, PERSONNEL FROM THE INDIANAPOLIS FIRE DEPT. DETERMINED THAT THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE ON TANK CAR HAS FROZEN OPEN.  BUILT UP ICE WAS KNOCKED AWAY FROM THE VALVE ALLOWING VALVE TO RESET AND STOPPING THE CONTINUOUS RELEASE OF PRODUCT VAPOR.  CAR WAS CLEARED TO DESTINATION AT APPROX. 1955 HOURS, JUNE 24, 1991.
LOADER SET METER WRONG.  SHOULD HAVE BEEN SET AT 3000 GALS. NOT 7000 GALS. SPILL WAS CONTAINED IN CUSTOMER'S WATER SEPARATOR.  ALL NECESSARY REGULATORY AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED.

column168: LOAD WAS PICKED UP ON JUNE 8, 1991 FOR DELIVERY TO SAUGET, IL.  LOAD LEFT PHOENIX, AZ. ON JUNE 9, 1991 AT 14:00, PERIODIC CHECKS OF LOAD WERE MADE ENROUTE.  ARRIVED AT MORIARTY, NM TED'S TRUCK STOP NEAR MID-NITE.  CHECKED UNIT AND WENT TO SLEEP IN BUNK.  ON 6/10/91 NEAR 08:00 AWOKE AND WHEN CHECKING UNIT FOUND SOME WET SPOTS ON GROUND AND TIRES.  OPENED THE DOORS AND THERE WAS A BAD SMELL LIKE ETHER.  CALLED INTO OFFICE AND NOTIFIED THEM.  UNIT WAS LEFT PARKED AND ENRAC ENVIRONMENTAL WAS SUMMONED TO THE SCENE TO MAKE THE NECESSARY CORRECTIONS FOR THE LOAD TO CONTINUE.  ENRAC IS A DIVISION OF CHEMICAL WASTE MANAGEMENT.  THE GROUND AND EQUIPMENT WERE CLEANED AND UNIT WAS RELEASED AT 17:30 ON 6.10/91 TO COMPLETE TRIP.

IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT 1 DRUM HAD SPLIT ON THE BOTTOMS OF THE SEAM AND HAD RUPTURED IN THE FINAL HOUR BEFORE DELIVERY.  THE DRUM MAY HAVE BEEN DAMAGED DURING THE LOADING PROCESS BUT DID NOT RUPTURE IMMEDIATELY. APPROXIMATLEY 45 GAL. WAS LOST, AN EMERGENCY CREW SUPPLIED BY SHIPPER CAME TO SCENE AND AFFECTED CLEANUP AND DECONTAMIANTION OF AREA AND TRAILER. OTHER DRUMS HAD SMALL AMOUNTS THAT LEAKED OUT THE VENTED CAPS.

THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND THE SHIPPER AND FIRE DEPARTMENT WERE NOTIFIED.  REPRESENTATIVES OF THE SHIPPER FOUND THAT THE RUPTURE DISC WAS RUPTURED.  THE RUPTURE DISC WAS REPLACED AND THE CAR WAS ALLOWED TO CONTINUE ON TO IT'S DESTINATION.  MOVEMENT OF THE LIQUID INSIDE OF THE CAR WHILE IN TRANSIT IS BELIEVED TO HAVE CAUSED THE RUPTURE DISC TO BREAK.

UPON UNLOADING TRAILER CHECKER FOUND 1 GALLON OF HAIR SPRAY TO BE LEAKING DUE TO HEAVY FREIGHT TOP LOADED.  THE HAIR SPRAY HAD ALREADY EVAPORATED OUT, THE PAIL WAS TIGHTENED UP AND SENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.

SHIPMENT OF PAILS WERE DOUBLE STACKED ON TOP OF EACH OTHER AND DURING MOVEMENT OF TRAILER  TO SERVICE AREA FOR DELIVERY, SKIDS MOVED FORWARD PUTTING MORE WEIGHT ON CORNER OF PAILS CAUSING THEM TO CRUSH. SKID BEING PLACED ON TOP PLACED MORE WEIGHT ON CORNER OF BUCKETS TO CRUSH.  WHAT SPILLAGE OCCURRED ON LOT WAS DILUTED WITH WATER FOR MORE THAN FIFTEEN MINUTES PER MANUFACTURER'S INSTRUCTIONS.  MATERIAL THAT WAS LEFT IN TRAILER WAS RETURNED TO DOCK AND SWEPT IN PLASTIC BUCKET.  FERGUSON HARBER SERVICE DISPOSED OF.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 9:30 A.M. ON DUNDAY, JUNE 23, 1991, FR&P TRAIN R-413, CONTAINING THE ABOVE-MENTIONED CAR (ACFX 86990, 70TH CAR IN TRAIN), WITH CONSIST OF SEVENTY-SEVEN (77) CARS, DERAILED WHILE TRAIN WAS DEPARTING POTOMAC YARD.  IN ADDITION TO THE ACFX 86990 CAR BEING DERAILED.  THE ACFX 86990 WAS DERAILED AND PARTIALLY OVERTURNED, AND IN THE RERAILMENT PROCESS THE NORTH TRUCK OF THIS CAR WAS KNOCKED OFF CENTER RESULTING IN TRUCK OF CAR AND WHEEL OF TRUCK COMING TO RETS AGAINST BOTTOM OUTLET AND JACKET AT CENTER OF CAR FORCING OUTLET VALVE AWAY FROM ITS SEAT AND CAUSING A LEAK OF CONTENT FROM THE CAR TO BE INITIATED AT OUTLET. FOR THE FIRST SEVERAL HOURS FOLLOWING THE DERAILMENT, THE EXTENT OF THE LEAK WAS ESTIMATED TO BE APPROXIMATELY ONE (1) GALLON PER MINUTE.  THE LEAK LATER SUBSIDED TO A SLOWER PACE.  IT WAS ESTIMATED THAT ONE THOUSAND (1000) GALLONS OF THE PRODUCT WAS LOST FROM THE CAR DURING THE DURATION OF THE LEAK.  THE CAR CONTAINED 16,000 GALLONS OF PRODUCT.  SHORTLY FOLLOWING THE DERAILMENT, THE ALEXANDIRA DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED.  ALSO, THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER AND CHEMTREC WERE PROMPTLY NOTIFIED.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE SCENE, THE ALEXANDRIA FIRE DEPARTMENT PROMPTLY NOTIFIED.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE SCENE, THE ALEXANDRIA FIRE DEPARTMENTS PROMPTLY TOOK CHARGE IN SECURING AND PROTECTING THE AREA SURROUNDING THE DERAILMENT SITE AND WORKING WITH THE RAILROAD OFFICIALS AT THE SCENE (MAINLY SUPERINTENDENT MCGINLEY) IT WAS QUCIKLY ESTABLISHED FROM WAYBILL DOCUMENTS, ETC., WHAT THE CONTENTS WERE OF THE LEAKING ACFX 86990 CAR AND REQUIRED PRECAUTIONS TO BE TAKEN. ALL THE REQUIRED PRECAUTIONS WERE TAKEN AND THERE WERE NO INJURIES SUSTAINED IN CONNECTION WITH THE INCIDENT.  FOLLOWING THE AREA BEING FULLY SECURED AND THE PRODUCT OF THE LEAKNG CAR BEING IDENTIFIED, THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AUTHORIZED CLEAN-UP AND TRANSFER OF THE CONTENTS OF THE CAR AND CLEAN-UP OF THE DERAILMENT TO BE STARTED.  IT WAS ESTABLISHED THAT THE PRODUCT REMAINING IN THE ACFX CAR WOULD HAVE TO BE TRANSFERRED.  TO ACCOMPLISH THIS, O. H. MATERAILS WAS CALLED IN TO MAKE THE TRANFER.  AN EMPTY RAIL TANK CAR TO RECEIVE THE CONTENTS FROM THE LEAKING CAR WAS QUICKLY ORDERED THROUGH THE FR&P RAILROAD AND WAS RECEIVED SEVERAL HOUR FOLLOWING THE DERAILMENT.  THE EMPTY RECEIVING CAR, GATX 45008, WAS PROMPTLY PLACED BESIDE THE LEAKING TANK CAR AT THE DERAILMENT SITE FOR O. H. MATERIALS TO START THE TRANSFER.  DURING THE COURSE OF O. H. MATERIALS PERSONNEL TRABSFERRING THE PRODUCT, THEY EXPERIENCED DIFFICULTY ON SEVERAL OCCASIONS WITH THEIR PUMPING APPARATUS AND THE PROCESS OF COMPLETING THE TRANSFER WAS DELAYED.  IT WAS THEN NECESSARY FOR O. H. MATERIALS TO ORDER IN NEW PUMPING EQUIPMENT TO ACCOMPLISH OR COMPLETE THE JOB.  DURING MEANTIME, THE HULCHER COMPANY SPECIALIST IN RERAILING AND CLEARING RAILROAD DERAILMENTS, WAS ORDERED IN TO RERAIL THE CARS INVOLVED, INCLUDING THE LEAKING ACFX CAR.  THE HULCHER COMPANY ARRIVED ON MONDAY AND COMPLETED THE RERAILING OF ALL CARS, INCLUDING THE ACF

column168: JUNE 10, 1991 THE DRIVER WAS DRIVING ACROSS A UNIPROVED OIL FIELD ROAD.  IT HAD JUST RAINED & THE ROAD WAS SANDY, WHICH WAS IN GOOD SHAPE.  DRIVER CAME TO A CORNER AT APPROX 20 MPH, WHICH TURNED TO A CLAY SURFACE THAT WAS VERY SLICK.  THE PUP (TRAILER) SLID INTO THE DITCH & OVER TURNED.  APPROX 10 BBLS OF OIL SPILLED OUT OF THE DOME LID.  THE DRIVER BUILT A DEVERSION DYKE & CONTAINED THE SPILL.  WE USED ANOTHER TRUCK, PUMPED OFF THE OVERTURNED PUP, REMOVED IT & PUMPED UP OIL CONTAINED IN THE DYKE.  THE FOLLOWING MORNING WE BROUGHT IN A LOADER & DUMP TRUCK & HAULED OFF THE CONTAMINATED SOIL TO ENVROTECH DISPOSAL SITE LOCATED 12 MI SOUTH OF BLOOMFIELD, N. MEX.  RECEIVING # MT-ENVROTECH IS 91300.
THE FRANGIBLE DISC ON THE SAFETY VENT RUPTURED ALLOWING FUMING VAPORS TO ESCAPE THROUGH THE SAFETY VENT.

column168: ONE JUNE 24, 1991 AT APPROXIMATELY 8:30 AM THE SPILL WAS FOUND WHEN THE DRIVER WAS MAKING A DELIVERY.  A CASE HAD FALLEN FROM THE TOP OF A PALLET AND BROKEN.  LIQUID WAS LEAKING IN THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER BUT NONE HAD RELEASED INTO THE ENVIRONMENT.  THE DRIVER MADE THE INITIAL IDENTIFICATION AND CHECKED HIS PAPERWORK.  THE REGION OFFICE WAS NOTIFIED AND THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AT 8:51 AM, VERIFIED THE SPILL WAS HYDROCHLORIC ACID, CHECKED THE DRIVER'S PAPERWORK, NEUTRALIZED THE SPILL WITH SODA ASH AND CLEANED UP THE RESIDUE.  THE RESIDUE WAS PACKAGED SAFE FOR TRANSPORTATION. TO PREVENT SIMILAR SITUATIONS FROM OCCURRING IN THE FUTURE ALL PRODUCT STACKED ON PALLETS WILL BE SECUREL STRETCHWRAPPED.

WHERE DRIVER HAD TO UNLOAD, THE TANK WAS IN UNLEVEL GROUND WITH THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER DOWN HILL.  OUR DRIVER UNLOADED ALL HE COULD.  HE THEN GOT HELP FROM OPERATOR TO GET A CROSS TIE TO PLACE UNDER THE DOLLY LEGS ON TAILER.  WE DISOCNNECTED FROM THE TRAILER AND RAISED THE FRONT END UP.  WE RECONNECTED AND STARTED TO FINISH UNLOADING.  OPERATOR TOLD DRIVER THE TANK WAS OVERFLOWING.  DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CLOSED DOWN ALL UNLOADING OPERATIONS. ABOUT 20-30 GALLONS OVER FLOWED INTO SPILL DAM AREA.  A & M SAID IT WAS THEIR FAULT AND WOULD CLEAN UP THE SPILL.

DISCUSSED THIS INICDENT WITH ALL EMPLOYEES AT OCALA TERMINAL - PROCEDURE IS NOW TO USE REGULAR HAND TRUCKS WITHOUT SHARP PRONGS OR EITHER ROLL DRUM ON A PALLET AND MOVE WITH A FORKLIFT. column168: THIS REPORT CONCERS A ONE VEHICLE INJURY ACCIDENT THAT ACCURRED STATE ROUTE 74 AT MILE POST 0.2, AT APPROXIMATELY 0530 HOURS.  STATE ROUTE 74 AT THIS LOCATION CONSISTS OF ONE WESTBOUND LANE WITH AN EXTENDED ASPHALT AREA.  IT IS SEPARATED FROM ONE EASTBOUND LANE WITH AN EXTENDED APSHALT AREA BY SOLID DOUBLE YELLOW LINES.  AT THIS LOCATION THE ROADWAY CURVES TO THE LEFT FOR WESTBOUND TRAFFIC.  EAST OF WHERE THE CURVE STARTS, REGULATRY SIGNS ARE LOCATED INDICATING TO REDUCE SPEED AHEAD.  A SPEED LIMIT SIGN OF 35 M.P.H. AND A WARNING SIGN INDICATING A STOP SIGN AHEAD IS ALSO LOCATED EAST OF WHERE THE CURVE STARTS.  ON THE ROADWAY SPEED BUMPS ARE ALSO LOCATED GIVING MOTORIST WARNING TO SLOW DOWN, FOR WESTBOUND TRAFFIC.  TRAFFIC CONDITIONS AT THE TIME OF THE ACCIDENT WERE LIGHT, THE WEATHER CONDITIONS CLEAR, AND THE ASPHALT ROAD SURFACE WAS DRY WITH NO APPARENT DEFECTS.  VEHICLE #1 IS A BLUE, 1988, PETERBUILT TRUCK TRACTOR, BEARING OKLAHOMA REGISTRATION, P77-195.  THE VEHICLE IS REGISTERED TO TRIAD TRANSPORT, INC., ADDRESS OF 1630 MCALESTER, OKLAHOMA.  THE VEHICLE SUSTAINED DAMAGE TO ITS ENTIRE RIGHT SIDE.  VEHICLE #1 WAS PULLING A GRAY, 1988, CMC SEMI TRAILER, BEARING OKLAHOMA REGISTRATION 3447-AB.  THE VEHICLE IS REGISTERED TO TRIAD TRANSPORT INC., ADDRESS OF 1630 MCALESTER, OKLAHOMA.  THE TRAILER SUSTAINED DAMAGE TO ITS ENTIRE RIGHT SIDE.  VEHICLE #1 WAS REMOVED FROM THE SCENE BY W.C. FIELDS TOWING AND IT WAS STORED AT 2011 WEST GLENDALE AVENUE, PHOENIX, ARIZONA.  VEHICLE #1 WAS TRANSPORTING A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SUBSTANCE, PCB, AND THE REGISTERED OWNER MADE ITS OWN ARRANGEMENTS TO HAVE THE SUBSTANCE CLEANED OFF THE ROADWAY. column42: HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCE, LIQUID OR SOLID, N.O.S. OR ORM-E, LIQUID OR SOLID, N.O.S.
column168: THE INCIDENT OCCURRED ON THURSDAY, JUNE 20TH, 1991, AT APPROXIMATELY 7:40AM.  THE TANK IN QUESTION WAS LOADED WITH COAL TAR ROOFING PITCH, FOR WHICH IT WAS SPECIFICALLY DESIGNED.  IT IS GENERAL CONCENSUS THAT THE PRODUCT TEMPERATURE EXCEEDED THE MAXIMUN ALLOWABLE 500 DEGREE LIMIT, FOR THIS SPECIFIC TANK.  THE SOLE CONDITION IN CAUSING THE TANK TO RUPTURE WOULD, THEREFORE, BE CONCLUDED AS THE STRESS OF THE EXTREME HEAT.  THE TANK BEGAN TO LEAK IMMEDIATELY UPON THE DEPARTURE OF THE ALLIED-SIGNAL PLANT. NORMAL LOADING TEMPERATURES FOR THIS PRODUCT RANGE BETWEN 300 DEGREES AND 350 DEGREES.  HOWEVER, THIS OCCURRANCE, THOUGH A RARITY, WAS DUE TO THE EXCEEDED ALLOWABLE TEMPERATURE BEING LOADED INTO THE TANK.  THE FUTURE WILL REQUIRE US TO EXAMINE AND QUESTION MORE CLOSELY THE PRODUCT'S TEMPERATURE PRIOR TO THE LOADING PROCESS. ALL OF THE PRODUCT THAT HAD BEEN LOST, WAS RECLAIMED AND REPROCESSED BY THE SHIPPER.

column168: OUR DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE DESTINATION TO UNLOAD PRODUCT.  DRIVER PUMPED THE PRODUCT INTO THE WRONG TANK.  SINCE THIS TANK WAS NOT IN USE THE CUSTOMER HAD THE MANHOLE COVER OFF TO DRY THE TANK OUT.  CUSTOMER HAD CHANGED TANKS WITH NOTIFYING THE DRIVER.  THE MANHOLE WAS APX. 2/1/2 FEET FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK.  APX.  1046 GALLONS OF PRODUCT CAME OUT OF THE MANHOLE AT THE BACK OF THE TANK AND WAS CONTAINED WITHIN THE DIKE. CUSTOMER WAS USING HIS OWN PUMP TO UNLOAD.  AFTER PUMPING OUT THE DIKE, COMPANY PERSONNEL FLUSHED THE DIKE WITH WATER.  AFTER PUMPING OUT ALL WATER AND GASOLINE 912 GALLONS OF GASOLINE AND 3500 GALLONS OF WATER WERE RECOVERED.  THE REMAINING CONTAMINATED  SOIL WAS REMOVED AND REPLACED WITH CLEAN SOIL. THE CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS BROUGHT BACK TO THE BULK PLANT AND DISPOSED OF.  DRIVERS ARE NOW INSTRUCTED NOT TO UNLOAD INTO ANY ABOVE GROUND STORAGE TANKS AT A BULK PLANT FACILITY WITHOUT AN EMPLOYEE FROM THE CONSIGNEE BEING PRESENT.

BY THE TIME THE REPORTS WERE SENT IN I WAS NOT IN THE OFFICE AND THEY WERE FILED.  I DIDN'T DISCOVER THAT AN INCIDENT REPORT HAD NOT BEEN FILED UNTIL I WAS REVIEWING FILES FOR END OF YEAR SUMMARY.

column168: THIS CAR WAS DISCOVERED WITH 0 OUTAGE, 260 LBS PRESSURE AT 88 F.  THE PRODUCT WAS REMOVED FROM THE CAR APPX. 4 HOURS LATER.  THE TEMPERATURE HAD RISEN TO 110 DEGREE OUTSIDE.  THE CAR PRESSURE HAD RISEN TO 275 LBS. OF PRESSURE AT 90 F.  AS WE BEGAN TO DOWNLOAD THE PRODUCT FROM THE CAR THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE WAS BEGINNING TO LIFT.  A VERY MINOR RELEASE OF PRODUCT TOOK PLACE BEFORE WE COULD RELIEVE PRESSURE.  THE PRODUCT WAS REMOVED FROM THE TANK, THE OUTAGE WAS LOWERED TO A SAFE LEVEL, THE PRESSURE LOWERED TO 173LBS.  THE CAR WAS THEN ALLOWED TO MOVE ON INTO MEXICO FOR OFFLOADING.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED OF THE OVERLOADED CONDITION OF THE CAR.

JIM CRAFTON CALLED INTO THE TULSA TERMINAL AND TOLD ME THAT HE HAD A CHEMICAL SPILL.  I GOT THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE BOOK OUT & FOUND OUT WHAT TO DO.  I HAD THE DRIVER BRING THE TRUCK BACK TO THE TERMINAL AND WE PROCEEDED TO FOLLOW THE GUIDELINES IN THE BOOK.  I CALLED SOONER EMERGENCY SERVICE TO OUR LOCATION TO TAKE CARE OF DISPOSAL & CLEAN UP OF ALL ITEMS INVOLVED.

PACKAGE WAS REMOVED FROM SORT OPERATION BEACAUSE OF APPARENT LEAKAGE AND STAIN.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE INNER CONTENTS A 4.5 OUNCE AEROSOL CAN OF PAINT WAS FOUND INSIDE.  A PORCELAIN SIDE PLATE HAD CRUSHED THE CAN RELEASING THE CONTENTS.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS OR LABELLING ON THE OUTSIDE PACKAGE TO INDICATE THE INSIDE CONTAINER WAS A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. A SHIPPER'S CERTIFICATION WAS ALSO NOT PROVIDED WITH THE SHIPMENT.  THE FEDERAL AVIATION ADMINISTRATION WAS CONTACTED AT 317/247-2465 WHERE SPECIAL AGENT, DAVID KANE, WAS NOTIFIED OF THE PACKAGE.  THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD AND THE SHIPPER CONTACTED FOR DISPOSITION.

DURING LOADING OPERATIONS PACKAGE WAS SET ON THE FLOOR.  THE PACKAGE FELL OVER BECAUSE IT WAS TOP HEAVY AND UNBALANCED.  THE VALVE EVIDENTLY RUPTURED ON THE INSIDE CYLINDER.  THE CYLINDER PROPELLED THROUGH THE BOX WHERE IT TRAVELED ABOUT 60 FEET WHERE IT HIT A STEEL SUPPORT BEAM.  THE CYLINDER EXPLODED RELEASING A WHITE CLOUD OF GAS WHICH THEN DISPERSED.  A STEEL CATWALK AREA ABOVE THE IMPACT AREA WAS ELEVATED ABOUT 3 INCHES.  THE FEDERAL AVIATION ADMINISTRATION WAS CONTACTED AT 213/515-2218 WHERE SPECIAL AGENT, DAVE MURPHY, WAS NOTIFIED OF THE SHIPMENT.  THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED ABOUT THE INCIDENT AND THE PACKAGE HELD FOR DISPOSITION.

DOCKMAN, C. IWANSKI, LOADED ONE CARTON, 4 LBS., ON THE BACK OF HOUSTON TRAILER 19-1907.  DOCKMAN, F. WOODS, THEN DROVE OVER THE CARTON WITH A FORKLIFT.  THE CARTON WAS COMPLETELY DESTROYED AND CONTENTS SPILLED. HERITAGE REMEDIATION WAS CALLED AND CLEANED UP THE ENTIRE SPILL AND REMOVED PACKAGING WITH CLEANUP MATERIALS.  MR. WOODS RECEIVED A WARNING LETTER FOR DAMAGING FREIGHT.  MR. IWANSKI RECEIVED A NOTE TO FILE FOR IMPROPER LOADING OF FREIGHT.

column42: PAINT RELATED MATERIAL INCLUDING PAINT THINNING, DRYING, REMOVING, OR REDUCING COMPOUND
column168: ON 6/4/91 AT APPROXIMATLEY 0200 HOURS, SUPERVISOR DORIS CROTHERS REPORTED A SPILL OF AN OILY SUBSTANCE ON PACKAGE.  UPON ARRIVAL AT DOOR C-41A PACKAGE WAS SITTING ON THE NWH SLIDE.  EMPLOYEE JON JACOBS REPORTED TO MY SPILL PARTNER CERT II FRAN VANCE THAT THERE WAS AN ODOR AND THE VAPORS WERE CAUSING HIS EYES TO FEEL IRRITATED.  I, CERT 12, RHONDA CLONCH REMOVED PACKAGE TO OUTSIDE OF BUILDING.  UPON FURTHER EXAMINATION OF CONTENTS I FOUND 6-1 GALLON METAL CONTAINERS OF A SEALER STRIPPER.  ONE OF THE CONTAINERS HAD A DENT IN IT WHICH CAUSED THE UPPER SEAM OF CONTAINER TO SEPARATE. DURING FURTHER EXAMINATION, THE PRODUCT LABEL INDICATED THIS TO BE AN EXTREMELY FLAMMABLE SUBSTANCE.  THE SCREW TYPE CLOSURS WERE SEALED WITH A GLUE TYPE MATERIAL.  THERE WAS NO INDICATION ON THE PACKAGE OF A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL BEING SHIPPED.  NEITHER WAS THERE ANY DOCUMANTATION THAT ACCOMPANIED SHIPMENT.  UPON RELEASE BY FAA, THIS SHIPMENT WILL BE MOVED IN A DOT APPROVED CONTAINER.

ON 02/29/91, I, KAREN NICHOLS/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR FOR ABX AIR, INC.  145 HUNTER DR, WILMINGTON, OH 45177, INVESTIGATED SHIPMENT WAS PACKED IN FOUR FIBERBOARD BOXES ALL BOUND TOGETHER WITH PACKAGING TAPE. THERE WAS NO HAZARD MARKINGS OR LABELS AND NO SHIPPERS CERTIFICATION ON THE OUTSIDE OF THIS SHIPMENT.  THE FIBERBOARD BOXES DID HAVE AN ORIENTATION ARROW LABEL ON IT.  INSIDE CAPACITY (TOTAL EIGHT GLASS CONTAINER/24 OUNCE CAPACITY).  EACH GLASS CONTAINER HAD A PLASTIC, SCREW-TYPE LID CLOSURE. THERE WAS NO POSITIVE MEANS USED TO SECURE THIS PLASTIC LIF.  THE GLASS OF EACH CONTAINER WAS CLEAR AND THE PRODUCT INSIDE WAS A CLEAR LIQUID.  THREE OF THE GLASS CONTAINERS WERE LEAKING, TWO WERE COMPLETELY EMPTY, ONE HAD APPROXIMATELY 1 OUNCE LEFT IN IT.  THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK APPEARED TO BE LOOSE LIDS.  THERE WERE NO HAZARD MARKINGS OR LABELS ON THE INNER GLASS CONTAINERS.  THE GLASS CONTAINERS WERE PACKAGED IN THE FIBERBOARD BOXES IN SHREDDED PAPER.  ALSO, INCLUDED IN EACH FIBERBOARD BOXES IN SHREDDED PAPER.  ALSO, INCLUDED IN EACH FINERBOARD BOXES IN SHREDDED PAPER.  ALSO, INCLUDED IN EACH FIBERBOARD BOAX WAS A COPY OF A LATTER ADDRESSED TO THE CONSIGNEE (ATTACHED) IDENTIFYING THE PRODUCT AS AROMATIC SOLVENT.  THERE WAS NO APPARENT DAMAGE TO THE INNER OT OUTER PACKAGING OTHER THAN THE PRODUCT ITSELF BEING ABSORBED INTO THE FIBERBOARD.  AT THIS TIME WE HAVE BEEN UNABLE TO OBTAIN A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET FROM THE SHIPPER; THEREFORE, FOR THE PURPOSES OF THIS REPORT, I HAVE CLASSIFIED THIS PRODUCT AS A FLAMMABLE LIQUID, N.O.S., UN1993.  THIS SHIPMENT IS CURRENTLY BEING HELD IN OUR HAZ-MAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING RELEASE BY THE FAA.  UPON RELEASE THE SHIPMENT WILL BE TRUCKED TO ITS DESTIANATION IN A DOT APPROVED RECOVERY DRUM.
BOX WAS DROPPED AND BEGAN TO LEAK.  RICK ARKINS TREATED SPILL WITH FLY ASH TO NEUTRALIZE.

column42: HYDROGEN, PEROXIDE, AQUEOUS SOLUTIONS WITH MORE THAN 40 PERCENT BUT NOT MORE THAN 60 PERCENT HYDROGEN PEROXIDE (STABILIZED AS NECESSARY)
column168: THE PACKAGE WAS UNLOADED IN PRIMARY AND UPON SORTING, WAS FOUND TO BE WET. THE WET PACKAGE WAS SORTED BY MIKE GAZZANICA, WHO RECEIVED A SLIGHT BURN ON HIS HANDS.  MIKE WAS TREATED AT WESTBOROUGH EMERGI CARE AND SENT BACK TO WORK.  THE PLASTIC BOTTLES WERE IN PLASTIC BAGS IN THE BOX AND THE LEAK MAY HAVE STARTED WHILE THE PACKAGE WAS IN TRANSIT.  IN ANY CASE, A WET PACKAGE IS USUALLY CONTAINED IN A SPILL TUB AT THE UNLOAD FOR IMMEDIATE PROCESSING.  OUR UNLOADERS AND SORTERS WILL BE REMINDED IN "PCM'S" ABOUT WET PACKAGES  AND THE IMMEDIATE STOPPING UP OF A PROBLEM PACKAGE.  THE SHIPPER HAS BEEN NOTIFIED OF PROBLEM WITH LOOSE, VENTED CAP.

DICK GREEN HOOKED UP & STARTED TO PUMP FROM TANK TO TRACTOR.  HE THOUGHT HE HAD VALVES OPEN BUT HE DIDN'T.  HE PUMPED AGAINST A CLOSED VALVE & PUSHED THE HOSE FROM THE PRODUCT LINE, WHICH CAUSED A 20 GAL SPILL.  I REPORTED TO CONOCO & SYNDER OIL.  WE HAD A FRONT END LOADER PICK UP THE DIRT & PUT IT IN A PLASTIC TARP & COVERED IT.  SENT SAMPLER TO STEWART INC TO CHECK DIRT SAMPLES.  HAD A PEER GROUP MEETING AT CHEYENNE ON 6-19-91.

INFORMATION LISTED UNDERNEATH IS MY UNDERSTANDING OF EVENTS THAT OCCURRED ON 6/9/91. CF UNIT RRACTOR 10-429 TRL 15-9185 DOLLY 01-877 TRL 15-4147 TRAVELLING FROM CHARLOTTE, NC., TO RICHFIELD, OH.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1400 ON 6-9-91 CF DRIVER HENDERSON PULLED OF THE FANCY GAP EXIT OF INTERSTATE 77 AT CANA, CA. LEAKAGE WAS NOTED.  THE CANA FIRE DEPT. CALLED FOUR SEASONS INDUSTRIAL SERVICE FROM GREENSBORO, NC., TO HANDLE AS THE FLAMMABLE LIQUID ON PRO 748-204575 HAD LEAKED ONTO PRO 553-532184 (CLASS C EXPLOSIVES ((FIREWORKS)).  THE PAILS CONTAINING THE TOLUENE APPEARED TO HAVE BEEN PUNCTURED CAUSING THE LEAK.  JACK TOLBERT, H/M OFC FOR STATE OF VA., AUTHORIZED THE ENTIRE UNIT TO BE ESCORTED BY THE INDUSTRIAL SERVICE TO THE WYTHEVILE TERMINAL, LOCATED OFF I81 EXIT 24 (APPROXIMATELY 36 MILES). FOUR SEASONS REMOVED THE 2 LEAKY PAILS OF TOLUENE AND PLACED THEM IN A RECOVERY DRUM.  THEY ALSO REMOVED 6 CARTONS OF THE FIREWORKS THAT WERE SOAKED WITH THE LIQUID.  THE FLOOR OF THE TRILER WAS DRIED AND THE UNIT LATER WAS DISPATCHED FROM WYTHEVILLE TO ITS' FINAL DESTINATION.

column168: MANAGER, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS EMERGENCY RESPONSE, R.M. STINE NOTED CAR ON TRACK 206 (NEFF YARD) AND THE TANK SURFACE WAS COVERD WITH DRIED MATERIALS.  UPON INSPECTION, MANAGER STINE FOUND ALL EIGHT MANWAY SWING BOLTS LOOSE WITH ONE AT THE OPENING SIDE OF THE COVER PLATE HANGING DOWN (NOZZLE EQUIPPED WITH SAFETY CATCH ON THE TWO SWING BOLTS ON THE OPENING SIDE OF THE COVER PLATE, SO COVER PLATE MUST BE RAISED SLIGHTLY TO PROPERLY APPLY THE BOLTS).  COVER PLATE WAS OPENED AND LIQUID WAS TWO FEET BELOW THE "T" BAR ON NOZZLE.  THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS FOUND TO HAVE THE BOTTOM VALVE HALF OPEN AND THE PACKING GLAND NUT LOOSE. THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP WAS EQUIPPED WITH AN AUXILLARY BALL VALVE WHICH HAD A TWO INCK PLUG.  PLUG WAS LESS THAN WRENCH TIGHT.  MANAGER STINE SECURED THE MANWAY,  CLOSED THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE, TIGHTENED PACKING GLAND NUT, AND SECURED AUXILIARY BALL VALVE PLUG.  CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR FURTHER TRANSPORTATION.  CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED AND SUE MILLER (FMC/LAWRENCE, KS) REQUESTED CAR BE RETURNED TO THEIR PLANT.

column168: SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA.HM) GEOFF REEDER WAS NOTIFIED THAT CARMAN (SAM LOPEZ) HEARD A HISSING SOUND FROM TANK CAR GATX 83646 WHILE MAKING INSPECTIONS.  THE SOUND SEEMED TO BE FROM THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING.  BP CHEMICAL RESPONSE TEAM TEAM (VERN SHIRLEY) RESPONDED.  SSA/HM REEDER SPOKE WITH MR. SHIRLEY AND MR. SHIRLEY STATED THAT THE PRESSURE WAS 295 LBS (HE DID NOT TAKE AN OUTAGE READING).  THE BLOOMINGTON FIRE DEPARTMENT SPRAYED WATER ON THE CAR IN AN ATTEMPT TO COOL IT AND REDUCE THE PRESSURE.  THE PRESSURE DROPPED TO 279LBS.  (ABOUT 45 MINUTES LATER).  GATX 83646 WAS THEN TAKEN WAS THEN TO BP CHEMICAL FOR UNLOADING.  THERE WERE NO OTHER LEAKS FROM THE CAR.

SENIOR  SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIAL (SSA/HM) CLIFF HILL WAS NOTIFIED (BY AGENT FOR D.Q.& E) THAT TANK CAR GATX 18715 CONTAINING SODIUM HYDROSULFIDE, WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP PORTION OF THE TANK AT PERKINS, ARKANSAS.  SSA/HM HILL'S INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE PACKING GLAND ON THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE HAD NO PACKING WHICH ALLOWED LIQUID TO LEAK BETWEEN VALVE ROD AND ROD HOLDER ON THE CAR.  GLAND WAS REPACKED, AND NUT WAS TIGHTENED WHICH SECURED ROD AND STOPPED LEAK.  CONTACTED SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE CLINT LUNSFORD WHO WAS INFORMED OF THE INCIDENT.

column42: HAZARDOUS WASTE, LIQUID OR SOLID, N.O.S.
column168: OUR DRIVER, JACK RAY, SR., WAS INSIDE A VAN TRAILER, COUNTING AND INSPECTING HIS LOAD BEFORE LEAVING OUR YARD.  HE WAS WALKING ACROSS THE TOPS OF DRUMS, AND HE EVENTUALLY STEPPED ON THE TOP OF AN EMPTY POLY DRUM THAT ONCE CONTAINED HYDRIODIC ACID SOLTION.  THE BUNG WAS LOOSE ON THE EMPTY DRUM, AND A PUFF OF VAPOR WAS GIVEN OFF, SOME OF WHICH THE DRIVER INHALED.  FOLLOWING TREATMENT FOR PHARYGITIS AT A LOCAL CLINIC, THE DRIVER WAS REPRIMANDED FOR NOT WEARING HIS RESPIRATOR, WHICH HAD BEEN SUPPLIED TO HIM, FIT-TESTED AND WHOSE USE IS KNOWN POLICY.

column168: SSA/HM ARLA ROQUET WAS NOTIFIED BY MTO DAVE LANCASTER THAT TANK CAR UCLX 30108 WAS NOTED LEAKING PRODUCT FROMTHE TOP AS IT WAS BEING SET TO THE ODESSA TEAM TRACK.  ODESSA FIRE DEPT.  RESPONDED AND EVACUATED APPROXIMATELY 100 PEOPLE FROM A 1-BLOCK-SQUARE BUSINESS AREA.  THE EVACUATION STARTED AT 0725 HOURS AND CONCLUDED AT 0810 HOURS.  TRAIN MANAGEMENT (JOHN WEATHERLY), CHEMTREC, TX WATER COMMISSION, AND THE AIR QUALITY BOARD WERE NOTIFIED.  VULAN SHIPPER/ CONSIGNEE REPRESENTATIVE RAY HILL WAS ON-SECEN.  MTO LANCASTER WAS ON-SCENE TO REPRESENT UPPR.  VULCAN REPRESENTATIVES CHECKED THE CAR AND FOUND THAT 2 NUTS WERE MISSING FROM THE AIR-INTAKE FLANGE AND THIS HAD ALLOWED THE PRODUCT WITH 1300 POUNDS OF SODA ASH.  SOIL TESTS SHOWED THAT TOO MUCH SODA ASH HAD BEEN USED, SO VULCAN OPTED TO REMOVE APPROXIMATLEY 4 YARDS OF DIRT, STORE IT AT THEIR ODESSA FACILITY UNTIL THE PH WAS CORRECTED AND IT COULD BE PROPERLY DISPOSED OF.  THERE WAS NO DAMAGE, INJURIES, OR DELAYS INCURRED.

column168: 1400 HOURS, SUNDAY, JUNE 23, 1991, MR. RAY BREEDLOVE, MANAGER OPERAING PRACTICES, VILLA GROVE, ILLINOIS, CONTACTED SPECIAL AGENT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS S.D. WHITED ADVISING CAR ACFX 13411 LAST CONTAINED PHOSPHORIC ACID HAD BEEN REPORTED LEAKING BY RESIDENTS AND THAT HE HAD CHECKED CAR AND NOTED THAT A RUBBER GASKET WAS PARTLY OUT OF PLACE ON CAR.  DEPARTED DOLTON 1400 HOURS, SAME DATE ARRIVING VILLA GROVE 1640 HOURS, FOUND GASKET ON QUICK FILL MANWAY COVER NOT PROPERLY APPLIED AND HANDLE BOLT LOOSE. REARRANGED GASKET AND SECURED HANDLE BOLT.  CAR RELEASED FOR DESTINATION AT 1645 SAME DATE.  MR. JOE DEBNAM AT CHEMTREC NOTIFIED AT 1720 HOURS SAME DATE.

A CLOSED VEHICLE (I.D. 2FTEF26H7FCB09053), NAMELY A FORD 250 PICK-UP WITH A LOCKED CAP 1985 MODEL, OPERATED BY GARY KIST (S.S.N. 143-60-9729) A TRAINED AGENT OF DEL-MED,INC. WAS TRAVELING WEST M I-78 AT AN ESTIMATED SPEED OF 50 TO 53 MPH (85 KM. PER HOUR) WITH A LOAD OD DOT-7A PACKAGES CONTAINING RADIOPHARMACEUTICALS.  A SECOND VEHICLE SUDDENLY SWERVED INTO THE LANE IN FRONT OF MR. KIST'S VEHICLE CAUSING HIM TO TAKE SUDDEN EVASIVE ACTION RESULTING IN HIS VEHICLE LEAVING THE PAVED SURFACE OF THE ROADWAY ONTO THE SHOULDER OF THE INTERSTATE ABOUT 150 YARDS BEFORE EXIT 13 IN BLOOMSBURY, N.J.  THE VEHICLE SUFFERED AN INSTANTANEOUS SHOCK PRESUMED BY THE DRIVER TO BE THE RESULT OF STRIKING A POTHOLE OR SOME OTHER ABSTACLE AS THE SHOCK SEEMED TO ORIGINATE ON THE BOTTOM OF THE VEHICLE.  STILL TRAVELLING AT THE STATED VELOCITY, MR. KIST RETURNED HIS VEHICLE TO THE ROADWAY AND CONTIUED HIS ITINERARY NOTING THAT THE VEHICLE WAS APPARENTLY UNDAMAGED BY THE SHOCK SINCE IT APPARENTLY WAS HANDLING PROPERLY WITHOUT SIGN OF ABNORMAL VIBRATION.  THE WEATHER CONDITIONS AT THIS TIME WERE CLEAR DAYLIGHT AND A DRY ROAD SURFACE.  MR.  KIST ARRIVED AT HIS NEXT DELIVERY POINT (WARREN HOSPITAL, PHILLISPSBURGM N.J.) AND NOTICED THAT THE ACCESS HATCH OF HIS BED CAP WAS OPEN.  HE IMMEDIATLEY PERFORMED A PAY LOAD INVENTORY AND FOUND THAT TWO PACKAGES WERE MISSING.  HE NOTIFIED MIKE WADDELL, THE DEL-MED DISPATCHER AT THE SOUTH PLAINFIELD , N.J. FACILITY WHO SENT TWO INDIVIDUALS TO RESTRACE THE ROUTE AND ATTEMPT TO LOCATE THE MISSING PACKAGES.  THE INDIVIDUALS WERE MR. GARRETT KIST SR. (SSN 143-28-3307) AND DAVID HARDY (SSN 202-40-7474).  THE DEL-MED, INC. RADIATION SAFETY OFFICER MR. JOSEPH MOON (AUTHOR) WAS CONTACTED BY PHONE BY JOHN E HARDY, PRESIDENT AND C.E.O. AND ARNOLD LOMAX, PRESIDENT AND C.E.O. AND ARNOLD LOMAX, DEL-MED OPERATIONS MANAGER ON A TELECONFERENCE CALL.  THE SITUATION WAS RELATED AS FOLLOWS.  GARRETT KIST AND DAVE HARDY HAD CALLED FROM THE PAY PHONE AT THE 76 TRUCKSTOP IN BLOOMSBURY , N.J. AND NOTIFIED MIKE WADDEL THAT THEY HAD LOCATED THE TWO MISSING PACKAGES AT THE LOCATION THE TWO MISSING PACKAGES AT THE LOCATION OF THE HIGHWAY MISHAP AND HAD RECOVERED ONE PACKAGE SEEMINGLY UNDMAGED AND A SEVERLY CRUSHED PACKAGE AND ABOUT HALF IT'S CONTENTS FROM THE ROAD SURFACE USING THEIR BARE HANDS AND TRANSFERRED THE MARTERIAL TO PLASTIC BAGS WHICH WERE NOW LOCATED IN THE BACK OF THEIR VEHICLE.  AT THIS POINT, JOHN HARDY INSTRUCTED ARNOLD LOMAX TO GET SOME SLEEP IN PREPARATION FOR THE EVENTS OF THE NEXT DAY AND ASSUMED CONTROL OF THE FOLLOWING EVENTS.  WE THEN PICKED UP MIKE WADDEL ON OUR TELECONFERENCE LINE WHO WAS STILL IN CONTACT WITH DAVE HARDY AT THE TRUCKSTOP.  HE EVENTS AS RELATED WERE CONFIRMED AND THE TWO WERE INSTRUCTED TO WASH THEIR HANDS IMMEDIATELY AND WERE APPRISED THAT THEY WERE NOT PROPERLY EQUIPPED TO MAKE SUCH A RECOVERY SINCE THEY DID NOT HAVE SUFFICIENT MONITORING EQUIPMENT TO ASSESS CONTAMINATION LEVELS OR EXPOSURE RATES.  THE CONTENTS OF THE DAMA

column168: NEVADA PUBLIC SERVICE COMMISSION REPRESENTATIVE MIKE KULBACKI PHONED SSA/HM DENNIS ALM TO REPORT A LEAKING TANK CAR OF CAUSTIC SODA AT THE CYANCO SIDING, 7 MILES WEST OF WINEMUCCCA, NV.  SSA/HM ALM IMMEDIATELY TELEPHONED CYANCO (JIM RICE) WHO STATED HE HAD A TANK CAR OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE WHICH HAD PRODUCT ON THE OUTSIDE AROUND THE MANWAY COVER AND HE WAS REFUSING THE TANK CAR.  THE TANK CAR WAS NOT LEAKING AT THAT TIME. NEVADA DIVISION OF EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT WAS CONTACTED AT 1600 HRS.  SSA/HM ALM TRAVELED TO CYANCO AT 1930 HRS ON 6/28/91 AND EXAMINED TANK WHICH ACCOUNTED FOR THE LEAKING PRODUCT.  DUE TO HEAVY RAIN AT THE TIME, PRODUCT ON THE TANK CAR WAS WASHED OFF.  BECAUSE OF COMMODITY ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE TANK CAR, SSA/HM ALM CONCLUDED THE GASKET WAS MISSING AT TIME OF SHIPMENT. BOTH CHEMTREC AND TENNECO MINERALS CO. WERE NOTIFIED.  AT THE REQUEST OF JIM RICE, TENNECO MINERALS CO. IS ENROUTE AT THIS TIME TO REPLACE THE MANWAY LID GASKET. SHIPPING PAPERS APPEAR CORRECT AND THERE WERE NO OTHER VIOLATIONS.

YARD PAERSONNEL AT THE UPRR REISOR YARD, SHREVEPORT, LA. DETECTED A SMALL VAPOR RELEASE FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK CAR (ACX 18654).  THE TANK CAR WAS ISOLATED AT REISOR AND CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED.  SHIPPER'S REPRESENTATIVES (MANAGER OF TRANSPORTATION & DISTRIBUTION VANCE BARRY) RESPONDED AND DETERMINED THAT THE LEAK WAS FROM A "PINHOLE" IN THE WELD SEAM OF THE SUP BOWL AND THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK.  THE SHIPPER'S REPRESENTATIVES TRANSFERRED THE CONTENTS OF THE TANK CAR INTO TANK TRUCKS AND REDUCED THE PRESSURE STOPPING LEAK.  THE TANK CAR WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER'S FACILITY AT DONALDSONVILLE.

column168: TANK CAR NATX 268 WAS ONE OF SEVERAL CARS THAT RECEIVED A ROUTINE SAFETY INSPECTION AT THE UPPR UYARD AT ALEXANDRIA, LA.  THE INSPECTIONS WERE BEING CONDUCTED BY UPRR SSA/HM T.M. ROBINSON, ARR BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES INSPECTOR ED ERNEWEIN, AND UPRR CAR INSEPCTOR JOHN GRIFFIN.  THIS INSPECTION REVEALED A SMALL VAPOR LEAK FROM THE MANWAY GASKET.  ONE MANWAY BOLT WAS LOOSE AND THREE OTHERS COULD BE FURTHER TIGHTENED WITH A WRENCH. THE TIGHTENING OF THESE BOLTS SECURED THE CAR FROM LEAKING. GODDARD STATED THAT HE WOULD FOLLOW UP WITH THE PERSONNEL AT HIS FACILITY.

column168: SSA/HM LIBBY WAS NOTIFIED BY SSA TOM MORRISON THAT WHILE TRAILER MPZ250074 WAS BEING UNLOADED, IT WAS NOTED THAT 1 CARTON 30 LBS. CORROSIVE MATERIAL (MIXED HAZARDOUS FREIGHT) WAS CRUSHED AND LEAKING.  SSA/HM LIBBY'S INVESTIGATION DETERMINED THE MATERIAL TO BE 1 CARTON CLEANING LIQUID, LABELED "NA1760, SULFURIC ACID 30 LBS."  SSA TOM MORRISON ADVISED THERE WAS APPROXIMATELY 2 GALLONS OF SPILLED PRODUCT WHICH APPEARED TO BE COAGULATING. SSA/HM LIBBY CONTACTED RIEDEL ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (DAN LOBATO) AND REQUESTED THEIR ASSISTANCE TO CLEAN TRAILER MPZ250074 AND DISPOSE OF THE CONTAMINATED MATERIAL.  RIEDEL ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (MIKE FEY) ADVISED THE 1 CARDBOARD AS WELL AS ALL LABELS ON THE BOTTLES WERE DESTROYED BY THE SULFURIC ACID'S CORROSIVE ACTION, PREVENTING HIM FROM OBTAINING INFORMATION RELATIVE TO THE MANUFATURE OF THE PLASTIC CONTAINERS.  MR. FEY ALSO STATED HIS FORCES CLEANED THE BOTTLES AND NEUTRALIZED THE TRAILER AND LOADING-DOCK FLOOR WITH BICARBONATE SODA.  HE PLACED ALL ITEMS IN A PLASTIC BAG AND DISPOSED OF SAME.

HARRIMAN CENTER NOTIFED SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS CLIFF SHUPE TO RESPOND AS HAZARDOUS MATERIALS WAS INVOLVED PER INSPECTION OF THE TRAIN CREW. TANK CAR GATX 9171 LOAD OF SODIUM SOLUTION WASTE HAD HEAD PUNCTURE AND THE EDUCTION PIPE SHEARED THE VALVE OFF RELEASING THE PRODUCT. column168: DRIVER WAS UNLOADING PRODUCT INTO ABOVE GROUND BULK TANK WHEN CAP CAME OFF OF OPPOSITE END OF "T" UNLOADING LINE.  HE IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN VALVES AND STOPPED DELIVERY OF PRODUCT.  HE CONTACTED MANAGEMENT AT CONSIGNEE AND PROCEEDED TO HELP IN CLEAN-UP EFFORTS.  THEY PLACED 3 BAGS OF FLOOR DRY ON PRODUCT INITIALLY.  THIS SOAKED UP 90% OF PRODUCT.  THE MPCA WAS CONTACTED (DOUG BELLEFIELD) FOR FURTHER CLEANUP EFFORTS.  THE BALANCE OF THE PRODUCT WAS SOAKED UP.  AND WAS GIVEN A CLEAN BILL OF HEALTH FROM THEM.  WE ARE NOW IN THE PROCESS OF REPLACEMENT OF THE ASPHALT AREA WHERE THE GASOLINE HAD FALLEDN.  NO PRODUCT RAN OFF THE ASPHALT SO THERE WAS NO GROUND CONTAMINATION.  WE RELAYED THE IMPORTANCE OF CHECKING ALL CAPS AND VALVES BEFORE UNLOADING TO ELIMINATE THIS TYPE OF PROBLEM AGAIN.  WE DID NOT FIND NEGLIGENCE ON THE PART OF THE DRIVER AS THE CAP SEEMED TO HAVE "POPPED" OFF WITHOUT ANY WARNING.

HAZ MAT RECEIVED REPORT OF LEAKING TANK CAR AT SIBERT YARD IN MOBILE, AL. CAR REPORTED LEAKING STEADY STREAM FROM BOTTOM OUTLET.  CAR WAS ISOLATED AND A BUCKET PLACED UNDER IT TO CONTAIN THE SPILLAGE.  SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC HUT WAS UNABLE TO RESPONSE.  HAZMAT CALL REIDEL PETERSON TO RESPOND. REIDEL CREW FOUND BOTTOM OUTLET CAP LOOSE; THEY TIGHTENED OUTLET CAP AND RECLOSED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE AND THE LEAK STOPPED.

THE INCIDENT OCCURRED AT CUSTOMER'S UNLOADING DOCK.  WHILE UNLOADING THE CUSTOMER'S ORDER THE FORK ON THEIR LIFT PUNCTURED A DRUM PF 1,1,1 TRI. TEN GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  THE DRIVER, THOMAS MINOR, CALLED AND REPORTED THE RELEASE TO LARRY DUVALL AS SOON AS THE SPILL HAD BEEN CONTAINED.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED WITH ABSORBENT MATERIALS AND WAS COMPLETED BEFORE THE DRIVER LEFT THE CUSTOMER'S LOCATION.  NO FURTHER ASSISTANCE WAS REQUIRED,PER MS HALEY OF DIVERSIFIED POLYMERS.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: OUR PICKUP TRUCK PULLING TWO ANHYDROUS AMMONIA NURSE TANKS WAS DESCENDING DOWN A STEEP GRADE WHICH HAD BEEN COVERED WITH LOOSE PEA GRAVEL.  THE BRAKES DID NOT HOLD ON THE GRAVEL WHICH CAUSED THE TRAILERS AND TRUCK TO JACK-KNIFE AND ONE OF THE TANKS ROLLED DOWN AN EMBANKMENT.  DURING THE ROLL-OVER, THE ROLL BAR WAS BROKEN OFF AND THE EXPOSED PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE SNAPPED OFF RELEASING APPROXIMATELY 250 GALLONS OF NH3.  THE IOWA DNR WAS NOTIFIED IMMEDIATELY AND AN INCIDENT REPORT (NO. 06241WPW1828) WAS COMPLETED.  THE PROPERTY OWNER WAS CONTACTED AND AN ASSESSMENT OF DAMAGE WAS CONDUCTED.  THE DAMAGED TANK WAS TOWED BACK TO ITS ORIGIN.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES RESULTING FROM EITHER THE VEHICLE ACCIDENT OR THIS RELEASE.

column168: ON JULY 25, 1991, ROBIN POOL DELIVERED A PARCEL TO 707 MAIN ST., LA PUSH WA. 98350.  THIS PACKAGE HAD A NOTE ATTACHED TO IT, INSTRUCTING HIM TO DELIVER AS IS.  THIS PACKAGE SHOWED SIGNS OF LEAKAGE.  AS THE DAY CONTINUED, ROBIN DEVELOPED A HEADACHE, BUT DID NOT ASSOCIATE IT WITH THE PARCEL. THE NEXT DAY ROBIN RECEIVED A CALL TAG FOR P/U AT WHICH TIME HE WAS INFORMED BY THE CONSIGNEE THAT AN EMPLOYEE; JAMES JACKSON, OPENED THE BOX IN THEIR SHOP NOTING THE BOX WAS DAMP.  AFTER 10 TO 15 MINUTES HE STARTED TO EXPERIENCE A SORE THROAT, A HEADACHE AND DIZZINESS.  THEIR OTHER EMPLOYEE RODNEY CHAPMAN, HAD TO DRIVE JAMES JACKSON TO FORKS GENERAL HOSPITAL.  HE WAS ATTENDED TO BY DR. JIM WIRS WHO INSTRUCTED HIM TO STAY IN THE FRESH AIR AND IF HE STARTED TO GET SICK OR STARTED TO COUGH TO CONTACT HIM; THIS DIDN'T OCCUR. AT THIS TIME ROBIN FELT THAT THIS PARCEL SHOULD NOT BE PICKED UP IN THE CONDITION IN WHICH IT WAS IN.  HE CONTACTED HIS SUPERVISOR, JEFF HALSTEAD THE FOLLOWING DAY JUNE 27, 1991.  JEFF INFORMED ROBIN THAT HE WOULD CONTACT LOYD SMITH, ACCOUNT EXECUTIVE, FOR THE AREA AND THAT IT WOULD BE TAKEN CARE OF. ON JUNE 28, 1991, I (LOYD SMITH) WAS INFORMED OF THE INCIDENT AND ATTEMPTED TO MAKE CONTACT WITH THE LAPUSH OCEAN PARK RESORT ON THAT DAY WITH NO SUCCESS.  ON JULY 1, 1991, I MADE CONTACT WITH JOANN PENN, MANAGER, AND WAS INFORMED THAT THEIR EMPLOYEE WAS O.K., BUT DID NOT KNOW WHAT TO DO WITH THE CONTAINERS.  I TOLD HER I NEEDED MORE INFORMATION ABOUT THE CHEMICALS.  CONCORD CHEMICAL CO. 7010 NW 23 WAY, GRAINSVILLE, FL. 32606 WAS CONTACTED ON JULY 2, 1991.  THEY GAVE ME THE INFORMATION ABOUT THE MAIN CHEMICAL IN THE PRODUCT, ISOPROPANOL AND KEROSENE.  I CONTACTED JOANN PENN ON JULY 3, 191 AND WAS INFORMED THAT THE CONTAINER WERE IN THE STORAGE SHED.  AT THIS TIME MADE AN APPOINTMENT TO COME OUT AND INSPECT THE PARCEL ON JULY 8, 1991.  THIS WAS CONFIRMED WITH HER. ON JULY 8, 1991 I ARRIVED AT LAPUSH AND INSPECTED THE BOX AND IT'S CONTENTS.  I FOLLOWED THE PROCEDURES WITH NEUTRALIZING THE BOX AND 1/2 GALLON OF THE CONTENTS ACCORDING TO THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE BOOK ON PAGE 26 AND 32. I COMPLETED THE D.O.T. HAZARDOUS MATERIALS INCIDENT REPOFRT AND A D.I.R.# 5869925, CALL TAG #1760069 ON JULY 9, 1991.

AT APPROXIMATELY 1815 HOURS, JUNE 14, 1991, R.D. BURRITT, SUPERVISOR AT THE CONRAIL ALBANY DIVISION CUSTOMER OPERATIONS CENTER IN SELKIRK, NEW YORK, RECEIVED A TELEPHONE CALL FROM CLYDE STROUP OF NIAGARA MOHAWK POWER. MR. STROUP ADVISED THAT HE WAS NOTIFYING CONRAIL, PURSUANT TO CFR-20, SECTON 205, THAT THERE WAS SMEARABLE RADIOACTIVITY DETECTED ON CASK CAR PNSX-1 WHICH HAD BEEN RETURNED EMPTY TO NIAGARA MOHAWK POWER COMPANY IN OSWEGO, NY ON JUNE 9, 1991 BY CONRAIL. ON JULY 31, 1991, CONRAIL WAS CONTACTED BY DOT/FRA INSPECTOR R. MCNAMARA INQUIRING AS TO WHETHER OR NOT CONRAIL HAD NOTIFIED THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER AND IF A DOT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS INCIDENT REPORT (DOT 5800.1) HAD BEEN SUBMITTED.  FURTHER DISCUSSION WITH DOT/FRA HAZARDOUS SPECIALIST L. FIORENZO INDICATED THAT THE DOT WOULD REQUIRE A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL INCIDENT REPORT FROM CONRAIL. THIS REPORT IS BEING SUBMITTED FOR INFORMATION ONLY.  CONRAIL CONTENDS THAT GIVEN THE CIRCUMSTANCES IT SHOULD BE THE RESPONSIBILITY OF NIAGARA MOHAWK TO NOTIFY THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER.  ADDITIONALLY, CONRAIL ALSO BELIEVES THAT THE RESPONSIBILITY OF COMPLETION OF A HAZARDOUS MATERIALS INCIDENT REPORT SHOULD BE WITH THE ORIGIN RAIL CARRIER, NOT CONRAIL.
